    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-11-25T11:24:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-11-25T11:24:00-05:00" n="348"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d348">
                <head>348. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in the United Arab Republic</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d348fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1964–66,
                        AID (US) <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>. Secret. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_BDC1">Bergus</persName> and approved by <persName
                            corresp="#p_HRA2">Hare</persName>. Repeated to Amman and <gloss
                            target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1966-11-25T11:24:00-05:00">November 25, 1966, 11:24 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>90878. Cairo’s 2907.<note n="2" xml:id="d348fn2">Telegram 2907 from Cairo,
                        November 24, reported that <persName corresp="#p_BLD2">Battle</persName>
                        called on <persName corresp="#p_FM5">Fawzi</persName>, told him of U.S.
                        concern over the situation in Middle East, and appealed for steps to
                        alleviate tensions by all countries interested in peace in the area. He
                        referred to a change in tone of the Egyptian press and to <gloss
                            target="#t_PLO1">PLO</gloss> statements as provocative and unhelpful.
                            <persName corresp="#p_FM5">Fawzi</persName> assured him of <gloss
                            target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> interest in peace but declared that recent
                        charges by <persName corresp="#p_TWE1">Wasfi Tell,</persName> required
                        answers in the press and other media. (Ibid., POL 32–1 ISR–JORDAN)</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HRA2">Hare</persName> lunched alone with <persName
                            corresp="#p_KM2">Kamel</persName> November 23. <persName
                            corresp="#p_KM2">Kamel</persName> made usual lengthy presentation, by
                        this time well known to Department and Embassy Cairo, re importance US aid
                        to <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>. At one point <persName
                            corresp="#p_KM2">Kamel</persName> stated US should not try to “starve
                        Egyptians.” <persName corresp="#p_HRA2">Hare</persName> rejoined sharply
                        pointing out fact we had given over one billion dollars worth of aid to
                            <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> as evidence of our desire to be
                        helpful.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Main thrust of <persName corresp="#p_HRA2">Hare</persName>’s remarks
                        centered around need dampen down internal situation in Jordan. <persName
                            corresp="#p_HRA2">Hare</persName> dwelled at some length at
                        inappropriateness <gloss target="#t_HKJ1">HKJ</gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> rep Farra’s trying to drag US domestic
                        politics into Jordan situation. (<persName corresp="#p_HRA2">Hare</persName>
                        dwelled on this point in hope that <persName corresp="#p_KM2"
                            >Kamel</persName> would see that it could apply equally to <gloss
                            target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>.) <persName corresp="#p_HRA2"
                            >Hare</persName> also referred to inflammatory behavior of <persName
                            corresp="#p_SA12">Shukairy</persName> and intimated that it was not in
                            <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>’s own best interest to allow
                            <persName corresp="#p_SA12">Shukairy</persName> “lead Egyptians around
                        by the nose.”</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
